@mingwandroid @jkroes I have no doubt that there is a user-based solution to this problem. The issue is that it should *not* be up to the user to figure out what "incompatible package families" are. Users are going to be reading instructions to "conda install X" and "conda install -c conda-forge Y" and they are not going to have any idea that mixing these two commands can break things.

I *don't* think conda-forge and defaults can ever aim to be binary compatible, because defaults tries to maximise performance even at the cost of using proprietary libraries, while conda-forge aims to use a fully open and free stack.

imho, the aim here should be for conda to keep track of the channel that each package comes from, and disallow dependencies to come from a different channel *unless* the package is pure-Python. I'm sure there are many edge cases that break my rule but I hope it's a good starting point for discussion.

